text.tspan: Did you notice that 25% of the cues were "invalid", that is,
they appeared on the opposite side of the GO stimulus?
Through a learning process, you start to associate the cue
and the target location. That said, at the current timing, you
would probably always respond more quickly to the cued location,
Press the space bar to exit
Press the space bar to continue
You will see a fixation point and two boxes.
Press the left key (A) if you see
a go signal in the left box, and the right
key (L) button if you see a go signal in the
right box. Every trial, you will see
an X, which is a cue. Do not respond to
it, just ignore it! There are 100 trials.
